.SH "NAME"
debmake \- program to make a Debian source package
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.sp
\fBdebmake\fP [\fB\-h\fP] [\fB\-n\fP] [\fB\-p\fP \fIpackage\fP] [\fB\-u\fP \fIversion\fP] [\fB\-r\fP \fIrevision\fP]
[\fB\-z\fP \fIextension\fP] [\fB\-b\fP "\fIbinarypackage\fP\fI[:type], ...\fP]"
[\fB\-D\fP \fIvalue\fP] [\fB\-e\fP \fIfoo@example.org\fP] [\fB\-f\fP "\fIfirstname lastname\fP"]
[\fB\-i\fP [\fBdebuild\fP|\fBsbuild\fP|\fBdgit sbuild\fP|\fBgbp buildpackage\fP|\fBdpkg\-buildpackage\fP| ...]]
[\fB\-m\fP] [\fB\-q\fP] [\fB\-v\fP] [\fB\-V\fP] [\fB\-w\fP \fI"addon, ..."\fP] [\fB\-x\fP [01234]] [\fB\-y\fP] [\fB\-B\fP]
[\fIURL\fP]
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.sp
\fBdebmake\fP helps to build the Debian package from the upstream source.
.sp
Normally, this is done as follows:
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
The upstream source is obtained as a tarball from a remote web site
or a cloned work tree using \(lq\fBgit clone\fP\(rq.
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
For a tarball, it is expanded to many files in the source directory.
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
For a cloned work tree, it is used as the source directory.
.RE
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
debmake is typically invoked in the source directory without any
argument.
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
The source directory is copied to ../\fIpackage\-version\fP/ directory.
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
If ../\fIpackage_version\fP\fB.orig.tar.xz\fP is missing, it is generated.
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
The current directory is moved to ../package\-version/.
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
Template files are generated in the ../\fIpackage\-version\fP\fB/debian/\fP
directory
.RE
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
Files in the ../\fIpackage\-version\fP\fB/debian/\fP directory should be manually
adjusted.
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
\fBdpkg\-buildpackage\fP (usually from its wrapper \fBdebuild\fP, \fBsbuild\fP, ...) is
invoked in the ../\fIpackage\-version\fP/ directory to make Debian source
and binary packages.
.RE
.sp
Also, \fBdebmake\fP can be invoked with an argument.  This argument can be \fIURL\fP
for a tarball hosted on a remote web site or for a source code accessed
by \(lq\fBgit clone\fP\(rq; or local \fIPATH\fP to the tarball or the source code.
.sp
Arguments to \fB\-b\fP, \fB\-f\fP, and \fB\-w\fP options need to be quoted to protect them from the shell.
.sp
Other tools also offer ways to obtain the upstream tarball and creating required symlink to build a Debian package depending on
your workflow.  For example, \fBorigtargz\fP, \fBmk\-origtargz\fP, \fBgit\-deborig\fP, and \fBpristine\-tar\fP.
.SH "POSITIONAL ARGUMENTS"
.sp
\fIURL\fP
.RS 4
acquire the source tree from the tarball, the git repository or the source tree at this \fIURL\fP (or \fIPATH\fP) (if missing, the source tree uses the current directory)
.RE
.SH "OPTIONS"
.sp
\fB\-h\fP, \fB\-\-help\fP
.RS 4
show this help message and exit
.RE
.sp
\fB\-n\fP, \fB\-\-native\fP
make a native source package without \fB.orig.tar.xz\fP
.sp
\fB\-p\fP, \fB\-\-package package\fP
.RS 4
set the Debian package name
.RE
.sp
\fB\-u\fP, \fB\-\-upstreamversion\fP \fIversion\fP
.RS 4
set the upstream package version ("\fB@\fP" in \fIversion\fP is replaced by "\fB0~yymmddHHMM\fP" timestamp)
.RE
.sp
\fB\-r\fP, \fB\-\-revision\fP \fIrevision\fP
.RS 4
set the Debian package revision ("\fB@\fP" in \fIrevision\fP is replaced by "\fB0~yymmddHHMM\fP" timestamp)
.RE
.sp
\fB\-z\fP, \fB\-\-tarz\fP \fIextension\fP
.RS 4
set the tarball compression type for the missing upstream tarball, \fIextension\fP=(\fBtar.xz\fP|\fBtar.gz\fP|\fBtar.bz2\fP) (alias: \fBz\fP, \fBb\fP, \fBx\fP)
.RE
.sp
\fB\-b\fP, \fB\-\-binaryspec\fP \fI"binarypackage[:type], ..."\fP
.RS 4
set the binary package specs by a comma separated list of \fIbinarypackage:type\fP pairs.  Here, \fIbinarypackage\fP is the binary package name, and the optional \fItype\fP is chosen from the following \fItype\fP values:
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
